Great question! Let me break down the full lifecycle.

---

**Platform thread vs Virtual thread structure:**

```
Platform Thread:
┌─────────────────────────────────┐
│  OS Thread (heavy, ~1MB stack)  │
│  1:1 mapped to OS               │
│  Blocking = OS thread stuck     │
└─────────────────────────────────┘

Virtual Thread:
┌─────────────────────────────────┐
│  Java Object (heap memory)      │
│  Tiny stack (~few KB)           │
│  Mounted on Platform thread     │
└─────────────────────────────────┘
```

---

**When virtual thread is created:**

```
Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()
         │
         ▼
JVM creates a plain Java Object in HEAP
(just like any other object — very cheap)
         │
         ▼
Assigned to a Carrier Thread (platform thread)
(JVM maintains a small pool of carrier threads
 = number of CPU cores typically)
```

---

**What happens when it BLOCKS (e.g. your API call):**

```
Virtual Thread running on Carrier Thread
         │
         ▼
semaphore.acquire() / apiClient.fetchRecord()
         │
         ▼
JVM detects blocking call
         │
    ┌────┴────┐
    │UNMOUNT  │  ← virtual thread's stack
    │         │     saved back to HEAP as object
    └────┬────┘
         │
         ▼
Carrier Thread is NOW FREE
picks up another virtual thread
         │
         ▼
When blocking is done (API responds)
virtual thread is REMOUNTED on
any available carrier thread
```

---

**Memory layout in heap:**

```
HEAP
┌──────────────────────────────────────┐
│  VirtualThread@1  [stack snapshot]   │ ← waiting for API
│  VirtualThread@2  [stack snapshot]   │ ← waiting for DB
│  VirtualThread@3  [stack snapshot]   │ ← waiting for semaphore
│  VirtualThread@4  [running]          │ ← mounted on carrier
│  VirtualThread@5  [running]          │ ← mounted on carrier
│  ...1000 more objects...             │
└──────────────────────────────────────┘

CARRIER THREADS (only 8 — one per CPU core)
┌────┐ ┌────┐ ┌────┐ ┌────┐
│ C1 │ │ C2 │ │ C3 │ │ C4 │  ...
└────┘ └────┘ └────┘ └────┘
  ▲      ▲
  │      │
 VT4    VT5   (only 2 mounted at this moment)
```

---

**Continuation — the real mechanism:**

The virtual thread's stack is saved as a **Continuation object** in heap when unmounted:

```java
// Internally JVM does something like:
class VirtualThread {
    Continuation continuation;  // saved stack frames
    Object blocker;             // what it's waiting on
    State state;                // RUNNING / PARKED / BLOCKED
}
```

When API responds → continuation is resumed from exact point it left off.

---

**Your API flow internally:**

```
VT created (heap object ~few KB)
    │
    ▼
Mounted on Carrier Thread C1
    │
    ▼
apiClient.fetchRecord() ← network call, will block
    │
    ▼
JVM: "this is blocking, unmount"
Stack saved to heap as Continuation
C1 is FREE → picks up another VT
    │
    ▼
API responds after 2 seconds
    │
    ▼
Scheduler: remount this VT on C1 or C2 (whoever is free)
Resume from exact line after fetchRecord()
    │
    ▼
transformer.toLocalDto(record) ← runs
    │
    ▼
repository.save(dto) ← blocks again → unmounts again
    ... same cycle repeats
```

---

**Key numbers to appreciate:**

| | Platform Thread | Virtual Thread |
|---|---|---|
| Memory per thread | ~1MB | ~few KB |
| Creation cost | High (OS call) | Low (heap object) |
| Blocking cost | OS thread stuck | Just heap object parked |
| Max practical count | ~thousands | Millions |
| Who schedules | OS | JVM scheduler |

---

**One gotcha — Pinning:**

Virtual thread gets **pinned** (stuck to carrier, cannot unmount) when:

```java
synchronized (lock) {
    apiClient.fetchRecord(); // ← VT is PINNED here
                             // carrier thread is blocked!
}
```

Use `ReentrantLock` instead of `synchronized` to avoid pinning — this is why Semaphore (which uses `ReentrantLock` internally) is safe with virtual threads.

```java
// Bad with virtual threads
synchronized(this) { ... }

// Good with virtual threads
ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();
lock.lock();
try { ... } finally { lock.unlock(); }
```

This is the complete lifecycle — virtual thread is just a **heap object with a saved stack**, being mounted and unmounted on a small pool of carrier threads by the JVM scheduler.
